Dataset Struture¶

The dataset includes 113,937 rows (loan), 81 variables. Most of the columns are numeric, also there are some date/time columns. BorrowerAPR, BorrowerRate and DebtToIncomeRatio denote percentages and are represneted by decimals. There are also some ordered categorical variables like CreditGrade ProsperRating(Alpha). The ProsperRating is also represented with a numeric equivalent (0 - 7). ProsperScore that determines a risk score(1 - 10) for the loan.

The CreditGrade scale: NC, HR, E, D, C, B, A, AA The ProsperRating (Alpha) scale : N/A, HR, E, D, C, B, A, AA Both have simillar ratings

Intrest behind exploring the dataset.¶

Determining the main factors involved in calclating the interest rate.

First imprssions¶

According to the dataset dictionary, I strongly beleive that the columns CreditGrade and ProsperRating affect the interst rate directlty, ncomeRange and DebtToIncomeRatio are also a factor. Also the ProperScore and CreditScoreRange are correlated.

# Making CreditGrade and ProsperScore ordinal.
ordinal_dict = {'CreditGrade': ['NC', 'HR', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A', 'AA'],
                    'ProsperRating (Alpha)': ['N/A', 'HR', 'E', 'D', 'C', 'B', 'A', 'AA']}

for i in ordinal_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered=True, categories=ordinal_dict[i])
    df[i] = df[i].astype(ordered_var)

sb.countplot(data=df, x='ProsperRating (Alpha)', color=base_color, ax=ax[1]);
sb.countplot(data=df, x='ProsperRating (numeric)', color=base_color, ax=ax[2]);
sb.countplot(data=df, x='ProsperScore', color=base_color, ax=ax[3]);

plt.show()

ProsperRating both numeric and alpha appear to be normally distributed, and nearly simillar. The CreditGrade has slightly lower overall count than prosper rating. The most loans have a value score of C.

ProsperScore distribution is slightly different from the other ratings, with high counts in the 4 and 8 scores, probably it depends on diffenrent or more data than the other ratings.

Univariant Conclusion¶

Most of the variables had expected distributions and no outliers. However, ProsperScore had large spikes around the 4 and 8 values which were higher than the distribution center, also DebtToIncomeRation contained some extreme outliers, by adjusting the x-axis to only show a ratio between 0 and 1.25, the outliers were handled.

The distribution of the DebtToIncomeRatio was largely skewed due to the loans given to borrowers having very high incomes compared to their debt.

grid = grid.map_diag(plt.hist, bins=20);

Loans interest rate are highly correlated with ProsperRating (numeric). BorrowerRate and BorrowerAPR have the highest correlation with one another. Also, Showed by ProsperScore, a similar relationship between the interest rates and the ProsperRating, with some fluctuatuions. The most intresting part that there was no correlation spotted from DebtToIncomeRatio to the interest rate.

Apparently, there's a negative correlation between having a higher score and a lower interest rate, which makes much sense. This is obvious in the results for the ProsperRating (Alpha) variable where the decline was sharp.ProsperScore has a decilne, but the distribution of the BorrowerRate is generally more normal, and the IQR is generally larger for each of the rating.

Bivariate Discussion¶

Some of the credit risk score variables were related to the interest rate of the loans. This ws very obvious with the ProsperRating (Alpha). The results made much sense to real life scneanrios, where people with a better credit score will get a lower interest rate on their loans. As mentioned before, it was surprising how the DebtToIncomeRatio wasn't correlated to the interest rate.

Multivariate Exploration¶

Bivariate exploraation showed that ProsperScore and BorrowerRate weren't correlated much, so maybe multivariate exploration will help explain more on this.

In [21]:
fig = plt.figure(figsize=[8,6])

ax = sb.pointplot(data=df, x='ProsperRating (Alpha)', y='BorrowerRate', hue='ProsperScore',
                  dodge=0.4, linestyles='', palette='Blues');

This pointplot shows how the ProsperScore is distributed acorss the different credit risk scores in relation to BorrowerRate. It shows that ProsperScore might be using different criteria than the other credit risk scores, as suggested before.

In [19]:

This pointplot shows how the BorrowerRate changes for different loan Terms, split up by ProsperRating.

MultiVariate Discussions¶

Multivariate exploaration of the dataset explained why ProsperScore wasn't as highly correlated to the BorrowerRate. It uss different attributes to compute it's value. This was obvious after looking at the he ProsperScore and ProsperRating (Alpha) with relation to BorrowerRate.

Miltivariate exploration here showed something that wasn't clear in bivariate exploration; Inuitivley, one might think that shorter term loans should have higher interst as they introduce more risk. Howver the plot shows that the BorrowerRate increases as for longer Term loans.
